Virgil‚ having just revised and altered the Bucolics and Georgios, projected, with a view to giving the ultimate polish to the AEneid, which he had now eom- pleted, a tour in Greeee and Asia. With a dread almost prophetie, and an ardour not disproportionate, Horace addressed the ship which bore his departing friend :-— ‘

Sic te Diva potens Cypri,

Sic fratres Helenae, lucida sidera, Ventorumque regat pater,

Et serves animae dimidium meae ! ²

At Athens the poet met with Augustus, who was returning from Samos, where he had wintered after his Syrian expedition, to Rome. Changing his former intention, virgil determined to accompany his patron. On a visit to Megara he was seized with a sudden indisposition, which his voyage increased, and he died a few days aster his arrival at Brundusium,3 in his fifty-second year.
